    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I can help explain that. Your loan interest is calculated based on the outstanding principal balance. Every month, interest accumulates on the remaining balance, making the principal balance higher even if you're making a payment. When you start making your payments, these cover the interest first, and only the remaining amount goes towards reducing the principal. This means that initially, while the interest accrues, the principal balance grows, contributing to the feeling that little is being reduced. Exceptions like payments towards interest only or graduated assistant loans can alter this process, so it’s always important to know the specifics of your loan terms.",
